</noscript></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="2b892ec0285573b72fb47141def34480" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><BR><font class="h1font"> Prepare the Jump to Hyperspeed<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=13223'>Scott "sithborg279" Sykes</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=13223&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 16, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Prepare the Jump to Hyperspeed: First Look at Starship Battles<br />
<br />
<br />
For two years now, we have been enjoying the character based Star Wars minis game.  Yet that is only half the Star Wars experience.  Everyone has imagined flying an X-wing or TIE fighter.  That is why the X-wing and Rogue Squadron series has been so popular, along with being awesome games.  And now, we will get to recreate the massive space battles as seen in the movies.<br />
<br />
The Card<br />
<br />
Lets start off with the ship card.  First thing is the faction.  There are only two factions in this game, Light and Dark.  This is represented by the border color.  Light will have Red cards and Dark will have Blue.  It may be a bit disappointing that you can have Droid Starfighters with Star Destroyers, but I am willing to accept it, since helps make the faction more fleshed out.  Like A&A (a comparison that will fit a lot, apparently), you can also just keep to themes.<br />
<br />
The card will also contain the name and cost.  Standard fare.  The next important piece of info is the Class.  There are four classes of ships in the game, 1-4.  These represent the various size of the ships.  The size of bases also determines the class.  Starfighters are class 4, small warships and transports are Class 3 (large base), capitals are Class 2 (Huge base), and then there is the limited Class 1 ships.  There is currently only two Class 1 ships, the two Gargantuan (4x4) ships found in the starter, the Super Star Destroyer Executer and Mon Calamari Star Defender Viscount.  The Class of the ships will come into play when we talk about set up and movement.<br />
<br />
Hit Points is called Hull in this game.  This is how many points of damage the ship can take.  On the bigger ships, there are two numbers.  Home One, for example has a Hull rating of 6/4.  The bigger and more heavily armored ships will have double sided cards, Full-strength and Reduced.  Ships start on the Full-strength side.  The top number is the amount of damage the Full-strength side can take.  When it takes that amount of damage, you flip it to the Reduced side.  The second Hull number will the be the only one on the Reduced side.  This is how many more hits the ship can take before it is destroyed.  The Reduced side will generally have weaker stats as well, so while the ship isn’t done yet, it is weakened.<br />
<br />
Instead of an Attack rating, each ship will have a Weapons System.  Some of the larger ships will have more than one weapon system.  Each weapon system will have a an attack bonus modifier and a damage rating.  Some will also have extra rules, like Ion Cannons, which are +1 damaged against full strength ships.  Capitals will also have a Point Defense rating.  Point Defenses are a special ability of Capitals to defend themselves from starfighters.  We will cover that more in depth with the gameplay.<br />
<br />
Rather than having only one Defense rating, ships will have four different faces.  Front, back, and the sides.  Each one can have a different defense rating.  The base of the figure will mark which is the front side, and then mark the quarters of the ship.  Which will be important, since a ship needs a LOS to the side to target it with weapons, and it will be important to maneuver ships to get an advantageous LOS and protect their vulnerable spots.  <br />
<br />
To wrap up, there is also the Special Abilities section and Command rating.  Special Abilities will have additional things a ship can do or additional bonuses.  The Command Rating will be on limited ships.  Not too much is known, since the rules up are pretty much the quick rules.  But it seems like you get one point, and the number is the class of ships it can affect.  More will be known once I get my hands on the Command Sheet.<br />
<br />
<br />
Gameplay<br />
<br />
Setup:  Lets start with the how you set up the game.  Light side places first, on the empty side of the map, then Dark side places on the planet side of the map.  You place all Class 1, 2, and 3 ships within 3 squares of the edge of the map.   Class 4 ships (fighters) remain off the board and in your fighter pool.  They come into play during the move phase.  After the setup, turns are separated into 3 phases, Initiative, Move, and Attack.<br />
<br />
Initiative Phase: This is pretty much the standard of all WOTC games.  You roll the d20 to see who goes first.  The winner moves second and attacks first.  Loser moves first and attacks second.  Currently, the winner is not allowed to choose.  Makes it a bit easier, though it eliminates some strategic thought.  We will see if that remains with the full rules, but it doesn’t bother me too much.<br />
<br />
Move Phase:  You move all your ships at once.  Ships have the speed of their class rating, so Class 1’s can move one square, Class 4’s can move 4 squares.  <br />
<br />
Class 1 & 2 Movement: A class 1 or 2 ship can turn 90 degrees or move forward 1 square for each square of movement it gets.  Turning has to be done before moving forward, and they cannot move diagonally.  <br />
<br />
Class 3 &4 Movement: A Class 3 or 4 ship can move diagonally, and on Class 3s, the facing is determined after the move.  Moving diagonally is the same as moving 1 square.  Class 4’s must end their move if the get adjacent to an enemy Class 4.   <br />
<br />
Ships can move through allied starships, though they cannot end in the same square.  Ships cannot move enemy ships.  Class 1 and 2s can displace Class 4s though.  The controller chooses the closest square to get out of the capital’s path.  <br />
<br />
After all the regular moves are made, you get to Launch Fighters.  Capitals have a Fighter Launch X rating in their special abilities.  This is the amount of fighters you can launch at this time.  Choose the number of Class 4s from your fighter pool, where you placed your Class 4s at the setup, and place them adjacent to the launching capital.  They cannot move this turn.<br />
<br />
Attack Phase:  The player who won Initiative gets to make all their attacks first, followed by the other player.  Since damage isn’t applied to the end, it doesn’t make a huge difference.  First, you have to do all your Point Defense attacks.  Each bigger ship has a Point Defense attack, where you get one attack against each adjacent fighter.  Each hit deals 1 point of damage.  This is quite important, since Class 4’s can’t be targeted by non-adjacent weapon systems.<br />
<br />
After you do all your point defense shots, you get to use your weapon systems.  A Class 1-3 ship can target any ship on the map, except for non-adjacent fighters.  Each weapon system a ship has makes an attack.  So if a ship has more than one weapon system, that ship will get more than one attack.  When you target a ship, you also have to determine which side you want to target.  It will be to your advantage to maneuver so a ship can see the more vulnerable sides of a ship, since each face will have a different defense rating.  On hits, record the damage that it will take, but it doesn’t affect anything yet.  Normal weapon systems can target adjacent fighters.<br />
<br />
Class 4’s only get to target adjacent ships.  And as normal, 1s are auto misses, 20s are auto hits, and you get to add 1 damage.<br />
<br />
Once all ships have fired their weapons, the damage is applied.  If the damage is less than the primary Hull rating, keep recording the damage, but don’t do anything.  If damage taken was equal or more than the primary, flip it to the Reduced side, and leave the extra damage on it.  If a ship took damage equal to it’s combined Hull rating, it is destroyed.<br />
<br />
I really like how the attacks work.  It means that whoever attacks first, doesn’t necessarily win and take out your ships before they can get a shot off.  Activations aren’t as much of a factor either.<br />
<br />
So there you have it, a first look at the Starship Battles game.  I am deeply impressed, and am looking forward to seeing some stats.<br />
